comments.body: Thanks, @regineheberlein ! I'll check out the records. And thanks for the reminder, though the rest of the collection is still onsite, so that holding should remain, correct?
The records look good. Thanks again!

Some preliminary considerations to discuss with DACS and Alma teams:
1. Alma currently only has item records for SC ReCAP collections, not for everything.
2. We are currently not sending items as part of the nightly aspace2alma. 
3. To automate this process, we would need to modify the nightly process to include items. Question: would we want to *only* include the ReCAP locations? Probably.
4. Because Alma doesn't reject duplicate barcodes that come in as part of an import job, we need to front-load a deduplication process. (Let's triple-check this. It is too stupid to be true.)
5. The silver lining is that everything that is going to ReCAP must be barcoded, so the deduplication can safely be done on barcode, even if Alma doesn't do it for us.
6. As @mzelesky suggests, we could run an export job for SC items in ReCAP locations that gets uploaded to lib-sftp. Question: what would be the failsafe in case the items export job or upload to lib-sftp fails? (An outdated file on lib-sftp would result in a duplicate items upload to Alma because it would not reflect items that have been imported to Alma in the meantime.) We need some sort of "burn after reading" mechanism.
7. The aspace2alma job would then have to grab the file from there first, dedupe on barcode, and send back to lib-sftp only the items not found in Alma. Failsafe could be that it doesn't find a file, it exits.
9. On the Alma end, we need to set the (currently manual) import job to run on a schedule

pulfalight.title: Make mockup for more clarity on the grouped collection results

comments.body:
Here's a first draft of a clearer grouped search results approach where sub components are distinguishable from their parent collections:

![pulfa-grouped-results.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5cba15f2e89c9c3b0c58e0d1/43878d95-ae8d-4939-b8e2-6039b448fe3c)
I like the indentation and the white space vs blue. I am finding the icons a bit confusing to know what level things are box vs folder vs item.

We had discussed the use of these icons when we initially began developing the site. I've always thought they were confusing and not helpful especially since we don't privilege containers in how we describe materials. I think displaying hierarchy/context, which I think is perhaps captured in this issue, https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/issues/1153, (see my comments there in particular) is more helpful.

@ccleeton  and @faithc just to clarify, are you suggesting we do away with the icons all together in the search results and simply provide the hierarchy/context through the breadcrumbs? That full breadcrumb seems important to the completion of this ticket. Was it withheld from this cycle's priority tickets' queue for a particular reason?

I think that appropriate icons for Collections, Series, and Components would allow people to distinguish among them, and I believe there is usability value in that, but I'm open to your thoughts on it.

I think we probably need to do some user testing before getting rid of the icons, but I'm personally not a fan. Ha 

I agree about the breadcrumbs. I don't think we withheld that ticket purposely; we may not have included it given how many tickets we had already earmarked aside from this one. I also just realized that it was related in drafting my previous comment.
Ok, sounds good. Other than the icons, how do you feel about the rest of the design, @faithc ?
I think it looks good!
